                    2025–2026 REGULAR SESSION</font></div><br clear="all"/><span id="bill_house_num"><div style="float: left; width:50%; font-weight: bold; "><span style="text-transform: uppercase; text-align:left;width:50%;"><b>
                Assembly Bill
              </b></span></div><div style="float:right; width:50%; text-align:right;"><span style="text-transform: uppercase;"><b>No. 1653</b></span></div></span><hr/><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><table style="border-collapse: collapse" cellSpacing="0" align="center" role="presentation"><tbody><tr><td id="bill_authors" align="center"><span style="font-weight:bold;">Introduced by Assembly Member Lackey<br/></span></td></tr><tr><td id="bill_intro_date" align="center" class="textcenter"><br/>January 28, 2026</td></tr></tbody></table></div><hr/><br clear="all"/><div id="title"><span style="font-weight:normal;font-size:0.9em;"> An act to add Section 51900.4 to the Education Code, relating to pupil instruction. </span></div><br clear="all"/><br clear="all"/><div align="center"><h2>LEGISLATIVE COUNSEL'S DIGEST</h2></div><br/><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0"><span id="subject">AB 1653, Lackey.
                          Pupil instruction: health framework: heat illness.</span></div><div><span id="digesttext"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">Existing law establishes the Instructional Quality Commission and requires the commission to, among other things, recommend curriculum frameworks to the State Board of Education.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">This bill would require the commission, during the next revision of the publication “Health Framework for California Public Schools,” to consider including, and recommending for adoption by the state board, specific content related to the prevention of, and recognizing and responding to the signs and symptoms of, heat illness, as
			 described, and, for those purposes, to consider relevant guidance issued by the State Department of Public Health and policies adopted by the California Interscholastic Federation, as specified.</div></span></div><span class="hidden"><h2>Digest Key</h2></span><span id="vote">
      Vote:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">MAJORITY</span>  </span><span id="appropriation">
      Appropriation:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">NO</span>  </span><span id="fiscalcommittee">
      Fiscal Committee:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">YES</span>  </span><span id="localprogram">
      Local Program:
      <span style=" text-transform: lowercase">NO</span>  </span></div><hr/><span class="hidden"><h2>Bill Text</h2></span><div id="bill"><div style=" text-transform: uppercase"><h2 style=" text-align: left;">The people of the State of California do enact as follows:</h2><br/></div><div id="s10.0012833401171414849"><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0" class="ActionLine"><h3 style="font-weight:bold; display:inline;">SECTION 1.</h3> Section 51900.4 is added to the Education Code, to read:</div><div><div id="id_5DBF3C46-0DC3-4E21-AD35-D426DC82DAC8"><div><p><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;"><h6 style="display:inline;">51900.4.</h6> (a) (1) During the next revision of the publication “Health Framework for California Public Schools” (health framework), the Instructional Quality Commission shall consider including, and recommending for adoption by the state board, specific content related to the prevention of, and recognizing and responding to the signs and symptoms
						of, heat illness.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) For purposes of paragraph (1), the commission shall consider relevant heat illness prevention measures, heat illness signs and symptoms, and heat illness responses, as addressed by guidance issued by the State Department of Public Health and policies adopted by the California Interscholastic Federation.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;">(b) For purposes of subdivision (a), all of the following apply:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(1) “Prevention of heat illness” includes, but is not limited to, measures to stay cool, hydrated, connected to others, and informed of heat alerts.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(2) “Recognizing the signs and symptoms of heat illness” includes, but is not limited to, all of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(A) A red or flushed face.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(B) Nausea.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(C) Muscle cramps.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(D) Headache.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(E) Dizziness.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(F) Fatigue or weakness.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(G) Confusion.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(H) Heavy sweating or the lack of sweating.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 1em;">(3) “Responding to signs and symptoms of heat illness” includes, but is not
						limited to, all of the following:</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(A) Stopping physical activity.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(B) Seeking shade or a cool area.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(C) Drinking water or otherwise hydrating.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(D) Cooling the body.</div><div style="margin:0 0 1em 0;margin-left: 2.5em;">(E) Notifying a teacher, staff member, or other responsible adult.</div></p></div></div></div></div></div></div></body></html>
